    <h2>SECTION A: Attempt any TWO question.</h2><h3>Question 1</h3>
<div><p><p>How can you use mathematical induction to prove statements? Use mathematical induction to show that sum of first n positive integer is<br />
$$\frac{{n(n + 1)}}{{2}}$$</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Mathematical induction is a powerful technique used to prove statements or formulas that are valid for all natural numbers. It consists of 4 steps :</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-roman;">
<li>Basic step</li>
<li>Inductive Hypothesis</li>
<li>Inductive Step</li>
<li>conclusion</li>
</ol>
<p>In this method, initially the valid first number of the series is check if they hold true or not. When the basic step is true inductive hypothesis is given where the n = k is considered true. Next step is considered as inductive step where n = k+1 is checked and proved true.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>Let P(n): $$ 1 + 2 + 3 + â€¦â€¦â€¦â€¦â€¦â€¦.. + n =\frac{{n(n + 1)}}{{2}}$$</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-roman;">
<li><strong>Basic Step :<br />
</strong>For n = 1,<br />
LHS = 1<br />
RHS = 1 ( 1 + 1) / 2 = 1<br />
Hence, LHS = RHS<br />
Therefore, P(n) is true for n = 1</li>
<li><strong>Inductive Hypothesis</strong>:<br />
Assume that P(k) is true.<br />
$$1 + 2 + 3 + â€¦â€¦â€¦â€¦â€¦â€¦.. + k = \frac{{k(k+ 1)}}{{2}}Â  Â â€”â€”- (i)$$</li>
<li><strong>Inductive Step</strong>:<br />
We need to prove that P(k+1) is true.<br />
$$1 + 2 + 3 + â€¦â€¦â€¦â€¦â€¦â€¦.. + k + (k+1)$$<br />
from eq (1) we can write, :<br />
$$ = \frac{{k(k+ 1)}}{{2}} + (k+1)$$<br />
$$ = \frac{{k(k+ 1) + 2(k+1)}}{{2}}$$<br />
$$ = \frac{{ (k+ 1)(k+2)}}{{2}}$$<br />
$$ = \frac{{ (k+ 1)((k+1)+1)}}{{2}}$$<br />
i.e. P(k+1) is true whenever P(k) is true.</li>
<li><strong>Conclusion</strong>:<br />
Therefore, By the principle of mathematical induction, P(n) is true for n, where n is natural number.</li>
</ol>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 2</h3>
<div><p><p>Explain linear homogeneous recurrence relation with constant coefficients. What is the solution of the recurrence relation a<sub>n</sub> = 6a<sub>n-1</sub> â€“ 9a<sub>n-2</sub> with initial conditions a<sub>0</sub> = 1 and a<sub>1</sub> = 6?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>A mathematical relationship that explains how a series of numbers is produced based on earlier numbers in the sequence is called a linear homogeneous recurrence relation with constant coefficients. In particular, the sequence&#8217;s subsequent number is a linear function of a predetermined number of earlier terms, with constant coefficients that remain constant.</p>
<p>A linear homogeneous recurrence relation with constant coefficients serves as the basis for numerous applications in computer science, mathematics, and combinatorial analysis. It offers a methodical approach to defining a sequence in which each term is dependent on terms that came before it.</p>
<p>To solve the recurrence relation</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">a<sub>n</sub> = 6a<sub>n-1</sub> &#8211; 9a<sub>n-2</sub></p>
<p>with the initial conditions <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">a<sub>0 </sub>= 1</span></span>Â and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">a<sub>1 </sub>= 6</span></span>, we can follow these steps:</p>
<p>The first step is to determine the recurrence relation&#8217;s characteristic equation. Assumed is a solution of the kind <span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><sub><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">n</span></span></span></sub><span class="vlist-s">â€‹ </span></span></span></span></span><span class="mrel">= </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">r</span><sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">, </span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">where r is a constant. Substituting this into the recurrence gives us:</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">r</span><sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">n </span></span></span></span></span></span></sup></span><span class="mrel">= </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">6</span><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">r</span><sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">n</span><span class="mbin mtight">âˆ’</span>1 </span></span></span></span></span></span></sup></span><span class="mbin">âˆ’ </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">9</span><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">r</span><sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">n</span><span class="mbin mtight">âˆ’</span>2</span></span></span></span></span></span></sup></span></span></p>
<p>Dividing through by <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">r<sup>nâˆ’2</sup></span></span>Â (assuming <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">râ‰ 0</span></span>) results in:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">r</span><sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">2 </span></span></span></span></span></span></sup></span><span class="mrel">= </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">6</span><span class="mord mathnormal">r </span><span class="mbin">âˆ’ </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">9</span></span></p>
<p>Rearranging this gives us the characteristic equation:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">r</span><sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">2 </span></span></span></span></span></span></sup></span><span class="mrel">&#8211; </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">6</span><span class="mord mathnormal">r +</span><span class="mbin">Â </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">9 = 0</span></span></p>
<p>Now, we solve the quadratic equation:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">r</span><sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">2 </span></span></span></span></span></span></sup></span><span class="mrel">&#8211; </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">6</span><span class="mord mathnormal">r +</span><span class="mbin">Â </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">9 = 0<br />
</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">r</span><sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">2 </span></span></span></span></span></span></sup></span><span class="mrel">&#8211; 2.3</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">r +</span><span class="mbin">Â </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">3<sup>2</sup> = 0<br />
</span></span>(r-3)<sup>2</sup> = 0</p>
<p>This gives us a double root:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">r = 3</p>
<p>The recurrence relation&#8217;s general solution for a double root r = 3 is:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span><sub><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">n</span></span></span><span class="vlist-s">â€‹ </span></span></span></span></sub></span><span class="mrel">=</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">c</span><sub><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">1</span></span></span><span class="vlist-s">â€‹ </span></span></span></span></sub></span><span class="mbin">+ </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">c</span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><sub><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">2</span></span></span></sub><span class="vlist-s">â€‹</span></span></span></span></span><span class="mord mathnormal">n</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mord">3<sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></sup></span></span></p>
<p>where <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">c<sub>1 </sub></span></span>and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">c<sub>2</sub></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">â€‹</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> are constants determined by the initial conditions.We now use the initial conditions to find <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">c<sub>1</sub></span></span><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">â€‹</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">c<sub>2</sub></span></span>.</p>
<p>Using <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">a<sub>0 </sub>= 1 </span></span>:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">a<sub>0</sub></span><sub><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">Â </span></span></span></span></sub></span><span class="mrel">=</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">c</span><sub><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">1</span></span></span><span class="vlist-s">â€‹ </span></span></span></span></sub></span><span class="mbin">+ </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">c</span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><sub><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">2</span></span></span></sub><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">0</span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mord">3<sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">0</span></span></span></span></span></span></sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight"> = <span class="mord mathnormal">c</span><sub><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="mord mtight">1Â </span></span></sub><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="mord mtight">= 1</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p>Using <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">a<sub>1 </sub>= 6 </span></span>:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">a<sub>1</sub></span><sub><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">Â </span></span></span></span></sub></span><span class="mrel">=</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">c</span><sub><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">1</span></span></span><span class="vlist-s">â€‹ </span></span></span></span></sub></span><span class="mbin">+ </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">c</span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><sub><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">2</span></span></span></sub><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">1</span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mclose">) </span><span class="mord">3<sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">1<br />
</span></span></span></span></span></span></sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal">a<sub>1 </sub></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight"><span class="mrel">= </span><span class="mopen">(1</span><span class="mbin">+ </span><span class="mord mathnormal">c</span><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><sub><span class="mord mtight">2</span></sub></span><span class="mclose">) </span>3<br />
<span class="mrel">6 = </span><span class="mopen">(1</span><span class="mbin">+ </span><span class="mord mathnormal">c</span><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><sub><span class="mord mtight">2</span></sub></span><span class="mclose">) </span>3<br />
</span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight"><span class="mopen">(1</span><span class="mbin">+ </span><span class="mord mathnormal">c</span><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><sub><span class="mord mtight">2</span></sub></span><span class="mclose">) = 2<br />
<span class="mord mathnormal">c</span><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><sub><span class="mord mtight">2 </span></sub></span>= 1<br />
</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p>Now substituting back <span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight"><span class="mclose"><span class="mord mathnormal">c</span><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><sub><span class="mord mtight">1</span></sub></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">â€‹</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> and <span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight"><span class="mclose"><span class="mord mathnormal">c</span><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><sub><span class="mord mtight">2</span></sub></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">â€‹</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span><sub><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">n</span></span></span><span class="vlist-s">â€‹ </span></span></span></span></sub></span><span class="mrel">= </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mopen">(1</span><span class="mord"><sub><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">Â </span></span></span></span></sub></span><span class="mbin">+ 1.</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">â€‹</span></span></span></span></span><span class="mord mathnormal">n</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mord">3<sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">n<br />
</span></span></span></span></span></span></sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight"><sub><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2">n<span class="vlist-s">â€‹ </span></span></sub><span class="mrel">= </span><span class="mopen">(1</span><span class="mbin">+ </span><span class="mord mathnormal">n</span><span class="mclose">)</span>3</span></span></span></span></span></span><sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">n</span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight"><br />
</span></span></span></span></span></span></sup></span></span></p>
<p>Hence, The solution of the recurrence relation is: <span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight"><sub><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2">n<span class="vlist-s">â€‹ </span></span></sub><span class="mrel">= </span><span class="mopen">(1</span><span class="mbin">+ </span><span class="mord mathnormal">n</span><span class="mclose">)</span>3</span></span></span></span></span></span><sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></sup></span></span></p>
</div>
<h3>Question 3</h3>
<div><p><p>What is shortest path problem? Use Dijkstraâ€™s shortest path algorithm to find the shorteszt path between vertices a and z in the weighted graph below:</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-43382 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/dijkstras-algo.drawio.png?resize=286%2C132&ssl=1" alt="" width="286" height="132"></p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>In graph theory, the shortest path problem isÂ the problem of finding a path between two vertices or nodes in a graph such that the sum of the weights of its constituent edges is minimized.</p>
<p>for given question,</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-43382 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/dijkstras-algo.drawio.png?resize=286%2C132&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="286" height="132"></p>
<p>Initially the node from where the traversal start is a and we consider the weight of a as 0 and weight of other node as âˆ.</p>
<div class="table_wrapper" style="overflow-x:auto;"><table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center;">Vertex</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center;">a</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center;">b</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center;">c</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center;">d</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center;">e</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center;">z</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center;">Weight</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center;">0</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center;">âˆ</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center;">âˆ</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center;">âˆ</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center;">âˆ</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center;">âˆ</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p>wt(d) = min (wt(d), (wt(a)+wt(a, d))) = min (âˆ, 0+2) = min(âˆ, 2) = 2<br />
wt(b) = min (wt(b), (wt(a)+wt(a, b))) = min (âˆ, 0+4) = min(âˆ, 4) = 4</p>
<p>As the weight of d is less than wt of b so, now we consider node d as the current node. After updating the table it will be as</p>
<div class="table_wrapper" style="overflow-x:auto;"><table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;">
