<h2>SECTION B: Attempt any EIGHT question.</h2><h3>Question 4</h3>
<div><p><p>Let us assume tha R be a relation on the set of ordered pair of positive integers such that ((a, b), (c, d)) âˆˆ R if and only if ad = bc. Is R an equivalence relation?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>The three properties of reflexivity, symmetry, and transitivity must be satisfied in order to ascertain whether the relation R defined on the set of ordered pairs of positive integers ((a,b),(c,d)) such that ((a,b),(c,d))âˆˆR if and only if ad=bc is an equivalence relation.</p>
<p><strong>Reflexivity</strong>:<br />
A relation <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">R</span></span>Â is reflexive if for every element <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">(a,b)</span></span>Â in the set, it holds that <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">((a,b),(a,b))âˆˆR.</span></span></p>
<p>For our relation:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><span class="katex-display">ad = bc becomes ab = ab</span></span></span></p>
<p>Since this is true for all <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">(a,b)</span></span>, the relation is reflexive.</p>
<p><strong>Symmetry</strong><br />
A relation <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">R</span></span>Â is symmetric if whenever <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">((a,b),(c,d)) âˆˆ R</span></span>, then <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">((c,d),(a,b))âˆˆR</span></span> as well.</p>
<p>Assume <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">((a,b),(c,d)) âˆˆ R</span></span>. This means:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">ad = bc<br />
</span></span></span></p>
<p>To show symmetry, we need to check if:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">cd = ab</span></span></span></p>
<p>Since <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">ad = bc</span></span>Â implies that both <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">adad</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span><span class="mord mathnormal">d</span></span></span></span> and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">bcbc</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">b</span><span class="mord mathnormal">c</span></span></span></span> are equal, we can also write this as:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">bc = ad</span></span></span></p>
<p>Thus, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">cd = ab </span></span>holds, and the relation is symmetric.</p>
<p><strong>Transitivity</strong><br />
A relation <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">R</span></span>Â is transitive if whenever <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">((a,b), (c,d)) âˆˆ R</span></span>Â and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">((c,d), (e,f)) âˆˆ R</span></span>, then <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">((a,b),(e,f)) âˆˆ R.</span></span></p>
<p>Assume:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">((a,b),(c,d))âˆˆR</span></span>Â implies <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">ad=bc<br />
</span></span><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">((c,d),(e,f))âˆˆR</span></span>Â implies <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">cd=ef</span></span></p>
<p>We need to show that:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">af = be</span></span></span></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>From <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">ad = bc</span></span>, we can rearrange to get <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">a = bc/d</span></span>Â if <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">dâ‰ 0</span></span>.</li>
<li>From <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">cd = ef</span></span>, we can rearrange to get <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">c = ef/d</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">â€‹</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> if <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">dâ‰ 0</span></span>.</li>
</ul>
<p>Now, substituting <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">c</span></span>Â from the first equation into the second equation does not directly lead us to <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">af = be,</span></span> but we can manipulate the equations. We know:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">ad=bc</span></span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">cd=ef</span></span></p>
<p>Now, from <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">cd=ef,</span></span>Â substituting <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">c=ad/b</span></span></p>
<p>Substituting <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">c</span></span>:</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">(ad/b)d = efâ€…â€ŠâŸ¹â€…â€Šad<sup>2 </sup>= befâ€…â€ŠâŸ¹â€…â€Ša(ef) = b(ef)â€…â€ŠâŸ¹â€…â€Šaf = be</span></span></span></p>
<p>Thus, the relation is transitive.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 5</h3>
<div><p><p>Define function. Let f<sub>1</sub> and f<sub>2</sub> be function from R to R such that f<sub>1</sub>(x) = x<sup>2</sup> and f<sub>2</sub>(x) = x â€“ x<sup>2</sup> . What are the functions f<sub>1</sub> + f<sub>2</sub> and f<sub>1</sub> . f<sub>2</sub>?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>An association between a set of inputs and a set of potential outputs is called a function. A function is a key idea in mathematics and many applications because it gives a systematic approach to correlate each input with a single output. A function assigns exactly one output to each input from the input set.</p>
<p>A function is often denoted by <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">f(x)</span></span>, where <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">ff</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">f</span></span></span></span> is the name of the function and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">x</span></span>Â is an input value.</p>
<p><strong>Second part</strong></p>
<p>given,</p>
<p>f<sub>1</sub>(x) = x<sup>2Â </sup><br />
f<sub>2</sub>(x) = x &#8211; x<sup>2</sup></p>
<p>now,</p>
<p>f<sub>1Â </sub>+ f<sub>2Â </sub>(x)<br />
= x<sup>2 </sup>+ x &#8211; x<sup>2</sup><br />
= x</p>
<p>f<sub>1Â </sub>. f<sub>2</sub> (x)<br />
= x<sup>2 </sup>(x &#8211; x<sup>2</sup>)<br />
= x<sup>3Â </sup>&#8211; x<sup>4Â </sup></p>
<p>Hence, f<sub>1Â </sub>+ f<sub>2Â </sub>(x) = x and f<sub>1Â </sub>. f<sub>2</sub> (x) = x<sup>3Â </sup>&#8211; x<sup>4</sup>.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 6</h3>
<div><p><p>Explain fuzzy set with example. How do you find complement of a fuzzy set?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>According to the mathematical idea of a fuzzy set an element may partially belong to a set rather than being a full member or not at all, , which is made up of elements with degrees of membership.</p>
<p><strong>Defination</strong> :<br />
Fuzzy set &#8216;A&#8217; of set x is denoted by and defined as A = { x, Î¼<sub>x</sub>(A) : x âˆˆ x }.<br />
where Î¼<sub>x</sub>(A) : X â†’ [0, 1] is membership function.</p>
<p><strong>Second part</strong> :</p>
<p>To find the complement of a fuzzy set A, denoted as Aá¶œ, we compute the membership function for the complement using the formula:<br />
Î¼<sub>á´€</sub>á¶œ(x) = 1 &#8211; Î¼<sub>á´€</sub>(x),<br />
where Î¼á´€(x) is the membership function of the fuzzy set A for each element x.</p>
<p>example :</p>
<p>Î¼<sub>á´€Â </sub>= 0.2 then,</p>
<p>Î¼<sub>á´€</sub>á¶œ(x) = 1 &#8211; Î¼<sub>á´€</sub>(x)<br />
Î¼<sub>á´€</sub>á¶œ(x) = 1 &#8211; 0.2<br />
Î¼<sub>á´€</sub>á¶œ(x) = 0.8</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 7</h3>
<div><p><p>What is congurent modulo? Determine whether 37 is congurent to 3 modulo 7 and wheather -29 is congurent to 5 modulo 17.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Defination</strong> :<br />
A mathematical relation known as <strong>congruent modulo n</strong> characterizes situations in which two integers divide by a positive integer n to yield the same remainder. We state that an an is congruent to b modulo n if two integers a and b, meet this requirement. This is expressed as follows:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">a </span><span class="mrel">â‰¡ </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">b</span><span class="mspace">Â </span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">mod</span></span><span class="mspace">Â </span><span class="mord mathnormal">n</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></p>
<p>This means thatÂ <span class="math math-inline"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">n</span></span></span>Â divides the difference betweenÂ <span class="math math-inline"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">a</span></span></span>Â andÂ <span class="math math-inline"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">b</span></span></span>, or formally:</p>
<div class="math math-display" style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">aâˆ’b = kâ‹…n</span></span></span></div>
<div>
<p><strong>Numerical part :</strong></p>
<p>According to question we need to check whether 37 is congurent to 3 modulo 7 or not.</p>
<p>here, we know that for 37 to be congurent it should satisfy</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">aâˆ’b = kâ‹…n</span></span></span></p>
<p>where a = 37, b= 3 and n =7 then,</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">37 âˆ’ 3 = kâ‹…7<br />
34 = kâ‹…7<br />
34/7 = k<br />
k = 4.85</span></span></span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>As 4.85 is a decimal value not an integer so we can say that<strong> 37 is not congurent to 3 modulo 7.</strong></p>
<p>Again, we need to check whether -29 is congurent to 5 modulo 17 or not.</p>
<p>here, we know that for -29 to be congurent it should satisfy</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">aâˆ’b = kâ‹…n</span></span></span></p>
<p>where a = -29, b= 5 and n =17 then,</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">-29 âˆ’ 5 = kâ‹…17<br />
-34 = kâ‹…17<br />
-34/17 = k<br />
k = -2</span></span></span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>As -2 is an integer so we can say that<strong> -29 isÂ  congurent to 5 modulo 17.</strong></p>
</div>
</div>
<h3>Question 8</h3>
<div><p><p>Define network flow with example. What are saturated edge, unsaturated edge and slack value?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>In graph theory, the movement of a quantity (such data, traffic, or goods) through a network is referred to as network flow. Usually, a directed graph is used to depict the network, where:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-roman;">
<li>Vertices : Points (such as cities, computers, or junctions) are represented by vertices (nodes).</li>
<li>Edges : Connections between those points are represented by edges (links), such as pipelines, data links, or roads.</li>
<li>Capacity : The maximum quantity of flow that can go through an edge is known as its capacity.</li>
</ol>
<p>example of network flow:</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class=" wp-image-43400 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/network-flow.drawio.png?resize=255%2C75&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="255" height="75"></p>
<p>If the flow through an edge has reached its full capacity, it is said to as <strong>saturated edge</strong>. This indicates that no further flow may cross this edge without going over its capacity limit.<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline;">Mathematically</span> : If the flow <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">f(u,v)</span></span>Â on an edge from node <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">uu</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">u</span></span></span></span> to node <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">vv</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">v</span></span></span></span> equals the capacity <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">c(u,v)</span></span>, i.e., <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">f(u,v) = c(u,v)</span></span>, the edge is saturated.</p>
<p>If the flow through an edge is less than its capacity, it is referred to as <strong>unsaturated edge</strong>. This indicates that more flow is still able to flow through this edge.<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline;">Mathematically</span> : If the flow <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">f(u,v) </span></span>is less than the capacity <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">c(u,v)</span></span>, i.e., <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">f(u,v)&lt;c(u,v)</span></span>, the edge is unsaturated.</p>
<p>The discrepancy between an edge&#8217;s capacity and current flow is known as its <strong>slack value</strong>. It calculates the amount of flow that can be forced through an edge before it saturates.<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline;">Mathematically</span> : Slack value <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">s(u,v)</span></span> of an edge is defined as:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">s(u,v)=c(u,v)âˆ’f(u,v)</span></span></span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 9</h3>
<div><p><p>Give an example of tautology and contradiction. Show that implication and contrapositive are equivalence.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>A tautology is a logical assertion that, regardless of the truth values of its constituent parts, is always true.</p>
<p>example : <span class="base"><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal">p</span><span class="mbin">âˆ¨</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">Â¬</span><span class="mord mathnormal">p</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>According to this assertion, &#8220;either p is true or p is not true.&#8221;</li>
<li>Since p can only be true or false, one component of the statement will always be true, hence it covers all possibilities.</li>
<li>The statement is therefore a tautology as it is always true.</li>
</ul>
<p>A logical statement that is consistently untrue, regardless of the truth values of its constituent parts, is called a contradiction.</p>
<p>example : <span class="base"><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal">pÎ›</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">Â¬</span><span class="mord mathnormal">p</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>According to this assertion, &#8220;both p is true and p is not true at the same time.&#8221;</li>
<li>P can never be both true and untrue at the same time.</li>
<li>Consequently, the statement is a contradiction as it is always untrue.</li>
</ul>
<p>We must demonstrate that the truth values of the implication statement, pâ†’q, and its contrapositive, Â¬qâ†’Â¬p, are identical in order to demonstrate the logical equality of the two statements.</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Implication</strong>: <span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">p</span><span class="mrel">â†’</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">q</span></span></span></span> means &#8220;if <span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">p</span></span></span></span>, then <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">q</span></span>.&#8221;</li>
<li><strong>Contrapositive</strong>: <span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord">Â¬</span><span class="mord mathnormal">q</span><span class="mrel">â†’</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">Â¬</span><span class="mord mathnormal">p</span></span></span></span> means &#8220;if not <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">q</span></span>, then not <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">p</span></span>.&#8221;</li>
</ul>
<p>An implication&#8217;s contrapositive is always logically equal to the implication. We can use a truth table to illustrate this.</p>
<div class="table_wrapper" style="overflow-x:auto;"><table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style="width: 16.6667%; text-align: center;"><strong>p</strong></td>
<td style="width: 16.6667%; text-align: center;"><strong>q</strong></td>
<td style="width: 16.6667%; text-align: center;"><strong><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">p</span><span class="mrel">â†’</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">q</span></span></span></span></strong></td>
<td style="width: 16.6667%; text-align: center;"><strong><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord">Â¬</span><span class="mord mathnormal">p</span></span></span></span></strong></td>
<td style="width: 16.6667%; text-align: center;"><strong><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord">Â¬</span><span class="mord mathnormal">q</span></span></span></span></strong></td>
