<h3>Question 10</h3>
<div><p><p>What is direct proof ? Give a direct proof that if m and n are both perfect squares, then mn is also a perfect square.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Direct proof</strong> is a technique for demonstrating a mathematical assertion by assuming that the premise or hypothesis is true and then logically drawing the conclusion from a series of sound steps. It is among the most basic and uncomplicated methods of proof.</p>
<p><strong>Second part</strong></p>
<p>let,</p>
<p>p â†’ q: If m and n are perfect square then mn is also a perfect square.</p>
<p>Let m and n be assumed to be perfect squares. According to what a perfect square is:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>An integer a exists such that ğ‘š = ğ‘<sup>2</sup>.</li>
<li>An integer a exists such that n = b<sup>2</sup>.</li>
</ul>
<p>now,</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">mn = ğ‘<sup>2</sup>b<sup>2<br />
</sup>mn = (ğ‘b)<sup>2Â  Â  Â </sup>i.e a perefct square.</p>
<p>which mean that p â†’ q is true i.e If m and n are perfect square then mn is also a perfect square is true.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 11</h3>
<div><p><p>What is product rule? How many strings are there of four lowercase letters that have the letter x in them?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Product Rule</strong> is used to determine how many possible outcomes there are for a task with several independent choices. According to this, if a task has m possible ways of being completed and another separate task has n possible ways of being completed, then there are mÃ—n ways to complete both tasks.</p>
<p><strong>Second part</strong></p>
<p>To solve the problem we calculate the complement i.e the strings devoid of the letter &#8220;x&#8221; and deducting that figure from the total number of possible strings, we will be able to solve this problem.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">There are 26 lowercase letters in the alphabet.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">The total number of strings of length 4 (with no restrictions) is:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">26<sup>4</sup> = 26 Ã— 26 Ã— 26 Ã— 26 = 456,976</span></span></span></p>
<p><span id="output-phrase~0~0" class="css-1m8t0fv"><span data-testid="output-word-0-0-0"><span class="css-0">SinceÂ </span></span></span><span id="output-phrase~0~1" class="css-1m8t0fv"><span data-testid="output-word-1-0-0"><span class="css-0">&#8216;x&#8217;Â </span></span></span><span id="output-phrase~0~2" class="css-1m8t0fv"><span data-testid="output-word-2-0-0"><span class="css-rh820s">isÂ </span></span><span data-testid="output-word-2-0-1"><span class="css-rh820s">eliminatedÂ </span></span></span><span id="output-phrase~0~3" class="css-1m8t0fv"><span data-testid="output-word-3-0-0"><span class="css-15iwe0d">fromÂ </span></span><span data-testid="output-word-3-0-1"><span class="css-15iwe0d">theÂ </span></span></span><span id="output-phrase~0~4" class="css-1m8t0fv"><span data-testid="output-word-4-0-0"><span class="css-15iwe0d">alphabet,Â </span></span></span><span id="output-phrase~0~5" class="css-1m8t0fv"><span data-testid="output-word-5-0-0"><span class="css-15iwe0d">thereÂ </span></span><span data-testid="output-word-5-0-1"><span class="css-15iwe0d">areÂ </span></span></span><span id="output-phrase~0~6" class="css-1m8t0fv"><span data-testid="output-word-6-0-0"><span class="css-15iwe0d">25Â </span></span></span><span id="output-phrase~0~7" class="css-1m8t0fv"><span data-testid="output-word-7-0-0"><span class="css-2yp7ui">alternativeÂ </span></span><span data-testid="output-word-7-0-1"><span class="css-2yp7ui">optionsÂ </span></span></span><span id="output-phrase~0~8" class="css-1m8t0fv"><span data-testid="output-word-8-0-0"><span class="css-15iwe0d">forÂ </span></span></span><span id="output-phrase~0~9" class="css-1m8t0fv"><span data-testid="output-word-9-0-0"><span class="css-15iwe0d">eachÂ </span></span><span data-testid="output-word-9-0-1"><span class="css-15iwe0d">letterÂ </span></span></span><span id="output-phrase~0~10" class="css-1m8t0fv"><span data-testid="output-word-10-0-0"><span class="css-15iwe0d">ifÂ </span></span><span data-testid="output-word-