<h3>Question 12</h3>
<div><p><p>Explain the matrix representation of relations with example.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>The matrix representation of a relation is a technique that uses a matrix of 0s and 1s to describe a binary relation between two sets (or within a set). When examining relations in terms of attributes like transitivity, symmetry, and reflexivity, this representation is especially helpful.</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Let <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">A={a1,a2,&#8230;,an} </span></span>and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">B={b1,b2,&#8230;,bm} </span></span>be two sets.</li>
<li>A relation <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">R</span></span>Â from set <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">A </span></span>to set <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">B</span></span>Â is a subset of <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">AÃ—B </span></span>(the Cartesian product), which means that for certain pairs <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">(a<sub>i </sub>,b<sub>j</sub>) âˆˆ AÃ—B</span></span>, the relation <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">R(a<sub>i </sub>,b<sub>j</sub>)</span></span>Â holds.</li>
<li>The matrix representation of relation <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">R</span></span>Â is an <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">nÃ—mn </span></span>matrix <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">M</span></span>, where:
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">M[i][j] = 1 </span></span>if <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">(a<sub>i</sub>, b<sub>j</sub>) âˆˆ R</span></span>Â (i.e., <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">a<sub>i</sub></span></span>Â is related to <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">b<sub>j</sub></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">â€‹</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>).</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">M[i][j] = 0</span></span>Â if <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">(a<sub>i</sub>,b<sub>j</sub>) âˆ‰ R.</span></span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Example</strong></p>
<p>Let <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">A = {1,2,3} </span></span>and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">B = {x,y}</span></span>. Suppose the relation <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">R</span></span>Â is defined as:</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">R={(1,x),(2,y),(3,x)}</span></span></span></p>
<p>The matrix representation of this relation <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">R</span></span>Â would be:</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$M_R = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 1 \\ 1 &amp; 0 \end{bmatrix}$$</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="minner"><span class="mord"><span class="mtable"><span class="col-align-c"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">â€‹</span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mclose"><span class="delimsizing mult"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">â€‹</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
</div>
